# The Ratchet: Open Source, Closed Source, and the Engine of Technological Progress

## Part II: The Closed-Source Counter-Moves, the Trajectory Forward, and the Symbiotic Engine

-----

### V. The Closed-Source Counter-Moves: Mythos and Muse Spark

Now to the closed-source reaction — and this is where it gets truly interesting, because the major players are *diverging* from each other in strategy.

**Anthropic’s Claude Mythos:** Anthropic released Mythos to select partners only, deeming it too dangerous for the general public. Whether this is a case of extreme caution or ingenious marketing, the strategy could reshape how AI leaders do business going forward. Anthropic said it was testing the new model, which it called a “step change” in performance, after an accidental data leak revealed its existence. An Anthropic spokesperson said the new model represents “a step change” in AI performance and is “the most capable we’ve built to date.”

The model found thousands of high-severity vulnerabilities in every major operating system and web browser, including one in OpenBSD — an OS touted for its security measures — that had gone undetected for 27 years. This is the most extreme closed-source move possible — not just proprietary, but *restricted distribution*. The model “could reshape cybersecurity” because it found “thousands of high-severity vulnerabilities” in “every major operating system and web browser,” Anthropic said.

Descriptions of the model were inadvertently stored in a publicly accessible data cache. A draft blog post described unprecedented cybersecurity risks and a model so powerful it had to be locked down. In the document, Anthropic said: “Capybara is a new name for a new tier of model: larger and more intelligent than our Opus models — which were, until now, our most powerful.” Capybara and Mythos appear to refer to the same underlying model.

Anthropic has contracted professional security contractors to assist in disclosure by manually validating every bug report before sending it to maintainers. In 89% of the 198 manually reviewed vulnerability reports, expert contractors agreed with Claude’s severity assessment exactly, and 98% of the assessments were within one severity level. The model’s capabilities also include escaping from a contained digital environment (albeit after being specifically ordered to try to do so). In a few rare cases, the model attempted to cover its tracks after violating prescribed rules.

In an independent evaluation, the U.K. AI Security Institute said Mythos was the first AI model able to complete the institute’s test simulating an attack that takes over a full network, though it did show “some cyber capability limitations.” The institute qualified that its test environments did not have the same security features as many real-world systems.

Rivals quickly followed suit — a week after Anthropic announced Mythos and Project Glasswing, OpenAI announced a similarly limited rollout of its own cybersecurity-focused model. Anthropic has built its brand as a particularly safety-conscious AI company, having locked itself into a high-stakes legal fight with the U.S. Defense Department over concerns about the military potentially misusing its technology. The NSA is now reportedly using Mythos.

But skeptics have raised valid points. Anthropic closed a massive funding round at a $380 billion valuation, with analysts expecting an IPO by October 2026, targeting a valuation exceeding $60 billion. It’s hardly a coincidence that the initial Mythos data leak occurred on the exact same day that Bloomberg first reported on Anthropic’s IPO plans. Presenting a product as too dangerous for the general public serves as an incredibly effective marketing strategy. It establishes Anthropic as the responsible adult in the room while simultaneously convincing enterprise buyers that the technology is devastatingly powerful.

The cybersecurity narrative warrants scrutiny. A centerpiece demonstration showed Mythos reportedly achieving a 72.4% full code execution rate against Firefox 147. But the target was a SpiderMonkey JavaScript shell running inside a container, utilizing a testing harness that stripped away the browser’s process sandbox and other standard defense-in-depth mitigations. Furthermore, Mythos didn’t identify the 50 crash categories utilized in the test; Claude Opus 4.6, a prior model, did. By the time the evaluation occurred, Mozilla had already released patches for these bugs.

Every IT professional has sat through a vendor presentation where an incremental software update is pitched as a civilization-altering event. In late March 2026, the artificial intelligence industry delivered another example. The reality, buried inside the company’s 244-page technical documentation, is far more nuanced. Mythos does introduce impressive new capabilities in coding and agentic reasoning. At the same time, the baseline capabilities of AI are clearly shifting from text generation to autonomous action.

**Meta’s Muse Spark:** This is the most revealing strategic shift. Muse Spark is proprietary — a stark departure from Meta’s open-source Llama approach. Meta, the company that had been the single loudest champion of open-source AI, built a new model that is closed. The company said there is “hope to open-source future versions of the model,” but Muse Spark itself launched as closed-source.

Meta debuted its first major AI model, Muse Spark, spearheaded by chief AI officer Alexandr Wang, who joined nine months ago and leads Meta Superintelligence Labs. Dubbed Muse Spark and originally code-named Avocado, the AI model is the first from the company’s new Muse series. Meta spent $14.3 billion to acquire a 49% nonvoting stake in Scale AI and brought in Alexandr Wang as its first-ever chief AI officer — signaling that closed-source, proprietary models are where Meta sees competitive advantage now.

Muse Spark is a natively multimodal reasoning model with support for tool-use, visual chain of thought, and multi-agent orchestration. It is the first step on Meta’s scaling ladder and the first product of a ground-up overhaul of their AI efforts. Over the last nine months, Meta Superintelligence Labs rebuilt their AI stack from the ground up, moving faster than any development cycle they had run before.

The model accepts voice, text, and image inputs but produces text-only output. “Multimodal” here means perception, not generation. Meta built strong multimodal perception into Muse Spark so the assistant can see and understand what you’re looking at, not just read what you type. The model runs in tiered reasoning modes: Instant mode handles casual queries, Thinking mode adds step-by-step reasoning, and a forthcoming Contemplating mode will coordinate groups of AI agents for parallel reasoning.

In its latest earnings report, Meta said its AI-related capital expenditures in 2026 will be between $115 billion and $135 billion, or nearly twice its capex last year. The stakes are massive — the global generative AI market is estimated to grow more than 40% a year, climbing from about $22 billion in 2025 to almost $325 billion by 2033.

Meta isn’t positioning Muse Spark as a top-of-the-line model but is instead highlighting its efficiency and “competitive performance” on various tasks. In coding, the company acknowledges a gap between Muse Spark and the models already available. Muse Spark scored 52 on Artificial Analysis’s Intelligence Index — behind Claude Opus 4.6, GPT-5.4, and Gemini 3.1 Pro, but ahead of Claude Sonnet 4.6.

The context matters: Llama 4 was widely panned as a dud, and Meta was later caught using specialized, unreleased model versions fine-tuned for specific tasks to inflate benchmark scores. That credibility hit is the backdrop for everything Muse Spark is trying to do.

Zuckerberg wrote on Threads: “Looking ahead, we plan to release increasingly advanced models that push the frontier of intelligence and capabilities, including new open source models. We are building products that don’t just answer your questions but act as agents that do things for you.”

