### Coda

The current AI model landscape as of April 2026 captures this tension in a single frame: GPT-5.4 leads on coding and long-form reasoning. Claude Opus 4.6 leads on benchmark breadth. Gemini 3.1 Pro leads on multimodal perception. Grok 4.20 leads on real-time web data with its multi-agent architecture. Muse Spark competes on efficiency and multimodal integration. And beneath all of them, open-source models — DeepSeek V4, GLM-5.1, Qwen3 — are closing the gap so fast that the gap itself may be the last generation’s metric.

The near-term advancement that matters most is the collapse in AI pricing. Frontier-level performance is now available at a fraction of 2024 costs. For most builders, the practical implication is clear: agentic workflows are no longer experimental. They are production infrastructure.

At the quantum level, Origin Pilot extends this logic into the next computing paradigm. At the standards level, MCP and the Agentic AI Foundation are building the open protocols that will determine whether the next era of AI is interoperable or balkanized. At the geopolitical level, the U.S.-China AI competition is playing out not through tariffs or sanctions alone, but through the strategic deployment of openness itself.

And at the deepest structural level, open source and closed source continue to do what they have always done: fuel each other. The combustion and the housing. The commons and the premium. The ratchet turns, the floor rises, and the boundary between what is free and what is proprietary moves upward once more.

The pattern doesn’t break. It escalates.

